00:00:00.350 --> 00:00:02.080
- Welcome to the Huberman Lab Podcast,

00:00:02.080 --> 00:00:04.930
where we discuss science
and science-based tools

00:00:04.930 --> 00:00:05.963
for everyday life.

00:00:09.520 --> 00:00:10.480
I'm Andrew Huberman,

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:13.340
and I'm a Professor of
Neurobiology and Ophthalmology

00:00:13.340 --> 00:00:15.330
at Stanford School of Medicine.

00:00:15.330 --> 00:00:17.780
My guest today is Dr. David Buss.

00:00:17.780 --> 00:00:19.830
Doctor Buss is a Professor of Psychology

00:00:19.830 --> 00:00:21.800
at the University of Texas, Austin,

00:00:21.800 --> 00:00:24.130
and he is one of the founding
members and luminaries

00:00:24.130 --> 00:00:26.840
in the field of evolutionary psychology.

00:00:26.840 --> 00:00:29.210
Doctor Buss's laboratory is responsible

00:00:29.210 --> 00:00:32.440
for understanding the
strategies that humans use

00:00:32.440 --> 00:00:35.520
to select mates in the
short- and long-term.

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:39.560
And he is an expert in sex
differences in mating strategy.

00:00:39.560 --> 00:00:41.640
His laboratory has explored for instance,

00:00:41.640 --> 00:00:44.540
why women cheat on their spouses

00:00:44.540 --> 00:00:45.820
or their long-term partners,

00:00:45.820 --> 00:00:47.580
as well as why men tend to cheat

00:00:47.580 --> 00:00:50.200
on their spouses and long-term partners.

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:52.760
He's also explored a
number of things related

00:00:52.760 --> 00:00:55.500
to the courtship dance that we call dating

00:00:55.500 --> 00:00:57.280
and securing a mate,

00:00:57.280 --> 00:00:59.240
including the use of deception

00:00:59.240 --> 00:01:01.420
related to proclamations of love

00:01:01.420 --> 00:01:04.410
or promises of finances
or sexual activity.

00:01:04.410 --> 00:01:06.760
Doctor Buss's laboratory
has also evaluated

00:01:06.760 --> 00:01:08.590
how status is assessed,

00:01:08.590 --> 00:01:11.590
meaning how we evaluate our own worth,

00:01:11.590 --> 00:01:14.680
and our potential as a mate, and who is,

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:17.850
let's just say within
range of a potential mate,

00:01:17.850 --> 00:01:20.030
both in the short- and long-term.

00:01:20.030 --> 00:01:22.740
For instance, today we
talk about how people

00:01:22.740 --> 00:01:24.890
don't just make direct assessments

00:01:24.890 --> 00:01:28.020
of their own and other people's
value as a potential mate,

00:01:28.020 --> 00:01:30.300
but also using the assessments of others

00:01:30.300 --> 00:01:32.300
to indirectly determine whether or not

00:01:32.300 --> 00:01:35.240
they stand a chance or
not in securing somebody

00:01:35.240 --> 00:01:37.200
as a short- or long-term mate.

00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:39.240
His laboratory has also focused on

00:01:39.240 --> 00:01:41.790
some of the complicated
and varied emotions

00:01:41.790 --> 00:01:44.150
related to mating,
love, and relationships,

00:01:44.150 --> 00:01:46.570
such as lust and jealousy.

00:01:46.570 --> 00:01:48.400
And he's extensively explored

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:50.270
something called mate poaching,

00:01:50.270 --> 00:01:52.570
or the various strategies
that men and women use

00:01:52.570 --> 00:01:54.920
to make sure that the person
that they want to be with,

00:01:54.920 --> 00:01:56.580
or the person they are with,

00:01:56.580 --> 00:01:59.570
is not with anyone else
or seeking anyone else,

00:01:59.570 --> 00:02:03.400
and indeed that other people
don't seek their mate.

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:05.110
Doctor Buss's work also relates

00:02:05.110 --> 00:02:08.610
to how biological
influences, such as ovulation

00:02:08.610 --> 00:02:10.460
or time within the menstrual cycle

00:02:10.460 --> 00:02:12.700
influences mate selection

00:02:12.700 --> 00:02:14.970
or tendency to have sex or not

00:02:14.970 --> 00:02:17.730
with a potential short- or long-term mate.

00:02:17.730 --> 00:02:20.710
And more recent work from
Doctor Buss's laboratory

00:02:20.710 --> 00:02:23.220
focuses on the darker aspects of mating

00:02:23.220 --> 00:02:24.680
and sexual behavior in humans,

00:02:24.680 --> 00:02:27.500
including stalking and sexual violence.

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:30.080
Today, we discuss all those topics.

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:33.370
We also discuss some of the
strategies that humans can use

00:02:33.370 --> 00:02:35.890
to make healthy mate selection choices,

00:02:35.890 --> 00:02:38.560
and for those that are already
in committed relationships

00:02:38.560 --> 00:02:40.220
to ensure healthy progression

00:02:40.220 --> 00:02:41.920
of those committed relationships.

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:43.490
In addition to publishing dozens

00:02:43.490 --> 00:02:45.840
of landmark scientific studies,

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:48.810
Doctor Buss has authored
many important books,

00:02:48.810 --> 00:02:50.010
a few of those include,

00:02:50.010 --> 00:02:53.540
The Evolution of Desire,
and Why Women Have Sex.

00:02:53.540 --> 00:02:54.860
And his most recent book

