00:51:32.490 --> 00:51:35.280
This is, Steve Gangestad, Randy Thornhill,

00:51:35.280 --> 00:51:38.500
and some others, Marty Hazelton,
a former student of mine,

00:51:38.500 --> 00:51:41.920
have advocated this dual
mating strategy hypothesis.

00:51:41.920 --> 00:51:45.750
And originally I was endorsed it,

00:51:45.750 --> 00:51:47.847
because the data seemed to support it,

00:51:47.847 --> 00:51:50.770
and we can get into which
data seemed to support it.

00:51:50.770 --> 00:51:53.840
But over time I became
more and more dubious

00:51:53.840 --> 00:51:56.010
about this hypothesis,

00:51:56.010 --> 00:51:57.900
and instead have advocated

00:51:57.900 --> 00:52:00.730
what I call the mate switching hypothesis.

00:52:00.730 --> 00:52:05.250
And so if you look at a
whole host of information

00:52:06.110 --> 00:52:08.420
around why women have affairs,

00:52:08.420 --> 00:52:09.720
it's not compatible

00:52:09.720 --> 00:52:11.860
with the dual mating strategy hypothesis.

00:52:11.860 --> 00:52:14.450
So, and is compatible
with the mate switching,

00:52:14.450 --> 00:52:18.720
that is, women who are looking to either

00:52:18.720 --> 00:52:23.520
divest themselves from
an existing mateship,

00:52:23.520 --> 00:52:26.820
or trade up in the mating market to a mate

00:52:26.820 --> 00:52:30.650
who's more compatible with
them or higher in mate value,

00:52:30.650 --> 00:52:34.590
or simply see whether they're
sufficiently desirable,

00:52:34.590 --> 00:52:38.500
so that it eases the transition
into the mating pool,

00:52:38.500 --> 00:52:41.950
