01:05:34.350 --> 01:05:35.893
than if you do use a condom.

01:05:37.800 --> 01:05:41.130
But whether evolutionary roots to this,

01:05:41.130 --> 01:05:42.550
I don't know, I mean condoms

01:05:42.550 --> 01:05:45.790
are probably relatively recent,

01:05:45.790 --> 01:05:47.370
or at least the widespread use of them

01:05:47.370 --> 01:05:50.630
are relatively recent
in evolutionary time.

01:05:50.630 --> 01:05:53.480
So I doubt we have adaptation
specifically for them.

01:05:53.480 --> 01:05:55.470
- No, and presumably before condoms,

01:05:55.470 --> 01:05:57.733
that one can only speculate
because as we say,

01:05:57.733 --> 01:06:02.113
when it comes to behavior,
there's rarely a fossil record,

01:06:03.311 --> 01:06:04.144
but sometimes there is,

01:06:04.144 --> 01:06:07.170
it would be the withdrawal
method of contraception,

01:06:07.170 --> 01:06:09.280
which a good friend of mine who studies,

01:06:09.280 --> 01:06:11.330
whose laboratory works
on reproductive biology,

01:06:11.330 --> 01:06:14.270
says the reason that's a
poor choice of contraception

01:06:14.270 --> 01:06:16.313
is because it was designed not to work.

01:06:17.530 --> 01:06:21.560
So note to those trying to
avoid unwanted pregnancy.

01:06:21.560 --> 01:06:24.170
So we talked a little bit about status

01:06:24.170 --> 01:06:27.230
in terms of what men and
women are selecting for,

01:06:27.230 --> 01:06:29.693
for different types of relationships.

01:06:30.530 --> 01:06:32.310
Is there anything else about status

01:06:32.310 --> 01:06:35.500
that you find particularly
interesting, and you know,

01:06:35.500 --> 01:06:38.780
what men are finding attractive
besides these, you know,

01:06:38.780 --> 01:06:43.780
waist to hip ratios and
quality of potential mothers

01:06:44.630 --> 01:06:45.463
and so forth.

01:06:45.463 --> 01:06:49.330
Are there any kind of a
hidden gems in the literature

01:06:49.330 --> 01:06:52.350
around this that I
might not have heard of?

01:06:52.350 --> 01:06:53.183
- Well, yeah.

01:06:53.183 --> 01:06:55.283
So you mean among,

01:06:56.360 --> 01:06:57.670
things like sex differences

01:06:57.670 --> 01:06:59.713
in what leads to high status?

01:07:00.570 --> 01:07:02.870
- For instance, or what,

01:07:02.870 --> 01:07:06.220
or perhaps things that are surprising

01:07:06.220 --> 01:07:09.210
in terms of what people are selecting for.

01:07:09.210 --> 01:07:11.530
Do people even know what
they're selecting for?

01:07:11.530 --> 01:07:12.830
Or is this all subconscious?

01:07:12.830 --> 01:07:15.970
Any and all of those topics
are of interest to me.

01:07:15.970 --> 01:07:18.410
- So we'll have to take
them in reverse order.

01:07:18.410 --> 01:07:21.240
You know, I think a
lot of it is conscious,

01:07:21.240 --> 01:07:23.700
but some of it is certainly unconscious,

01:07:23.700 --> 01:07:27.280
or there are elements which
are totally unconscious.

01:07:27.280 --> 01:07:29.450
So I mentioned one earlier

01:07:29.450 --> 01:07:31.130
where a man looks at a woman,

01:07:31.130 --> 01:07:34.510
he's not, he's aware that
he's attracted to her

01:07:34.510 --> 01:07:36.270
and attracted to her physical appearance,

01:07:36.270 --> 01:07:38.610
but he might not be aware of why.

01:07:38.610 --> 01:07:40.610
We didn't evolve to be aware of why,

01:07:40.610 --> 01:07:42.460
just like with food preferences,

01:07:42.460 --> 01:07:44.850
we find certain things delectable

01:07:44.850 --> 01:07:47.880
and other things nauseating,

01:07:47.880 --> 01:07:51.760
we don't understand the adaptive logic

01:07:51.760 --> 01:07:55.650
of why our food preferences
exist and why we have them.

01:07:55.650 --> 01:07:57.260
And the same is true of mating, you know?

01:07:57.260 --> 01:08:02.260
And so men find women with a
low waist-hip ratio attractive,

01:08:04.090 --> 01:08:07.890
but they might not, they almost rarely,

01:08:07.890 --> 01:08:09.770
rarely will they know, oh,

01:08:09.770 --> 01:08:12.330
low waist ratio is actually associated

01:08:12.330 --> 01:08:16.053
with higher fertility, lower
endocrinological problems,

01:08:18.350 --> 01:08:20.740
lower age, et cetera.

01:08:20.740 --> 01:08:23.990
So, we're sometimes aware of what we want,

01:08:23.990 --> 01:08:26.663
but we are unaware of why we want it.

01:08:27.750 --> 01:08:30.230
So, there are unconscious elements

01:08:30.230 --> 01:08:32.870
that the whole topic of status

01:08:32.870 --> 01:08:35.253
and what leads to high
status or low status,

01:08:35.253 --> 01:08:37.630
it's a topic I'm currently investigating,

01:08:37.630 --> 01:08:40.193
published a couple
scientific articles on it.

01:08:41.120 --> 01:08:43.470
And so maybe we'll hold off on that

01:08:43.470 --> 01:08:45.621
for a future discussion,

01:08:45.621 --> 01:08:48.450
but it intersects, I'll mention one,

01:08:48.450 --> 01:08:51.700
it intersects with mating
in interesting ways,

01:08:51.700 --> 01:08:54.860
in that higher status

01:08:54.860 --> 01:08:59.860
gives people the ability to choose

01:09:00.280 --> 01:09:02.340
from a wider pool of potential mates

01:09:02.340 --> 01:09:04.373
than they would if they have low status.

01:09:05.270 --> 01:09:08.740
And so one of the reasons
that people strive for status

01:09:08.740 --> 01:09:12.200
is because they have access
to more desirable mates.

01:09:12.200 --> 01:09:13.363
Conversely,

01:09:14.780 --> 01:09:19.287
having desirable mates endows
you with higher status.

01:09:19.287 --> 01:09:20.660
And so if you have,

01:09:20.660 --> 01:09:21.493
if you're a male,

01:09:21.493 --> 01:09:25.210
you have a very attractive
woman on your arm

01:09:25.210 --> 01:09:27.010
that leads to high status.

01:09:27.010 --> 01:09:28.410
And so there's a reciprocal link

01:09:28.410 --> 01:09:30.240
between status and mating in that way.

01:09:30.240 --> 01:09:31.840
And there've been studies where,

01:09:32.930 --> 01:09:37.930
say they pose a kind
of an unattractive guy,

01:09:38.020 --> 01:09:41.600
older unattractive guy, and
a stunningly beautiful woman

01:09:41.600 --> 01:09:42.800
as his girlfriend.

01:09:42.800 --> 01:09:46.560
And they say, well,
what's this guy all about?

01:09:46.560 --> 01:09:49.320
And they say, oh, he must
be very high in status.

01:09:49.320 --> 01:09:50.410
He must be very wealthy.

01:09:50.410 --> 01:09:52.893
He must have a lot going for him,

01:09:54.650 --> 01:09:59.103
whereas the reverse people don't
make the same attributions.

01:10:00.666 --> 01:10:02.430
And so there is an
interesting reciprocal link

01:10:02.430 --> 01:10:04.690
between status and mating success,

01:10:04.690 --> 01:10:07.600
where mating success leads to high status,

01:10:07.600 --> 01:10:10.850
and high status leads
to more mating success.

01:10:10.850 --> 01:10:11.840
- Over and over again,

01:10:11.840 --> 01:10:13.570
there are these instances
that you describe

01:10:13.570 --> 01:10:16.440
where the assessment of potential mates,

01:10:16.440 --> 01:10:18.240
sexual or long-term partnership,

01:10:18.240 --> 01:10:21.400
are being made in the contents

01:10:21.400 --> 01:10:23.050
of good statistical practices,

01:10:23.050 --> 01:10:24.730
looking at the choices of others

01:10:24.730 --> 01:10:27.376
as a readout of your own choices.

01:10:27.376 --> 01:10:28.890
This seems to be a theme

01:10:28.890 --> 01:10:31.670
that this is not being made
in a very narrow context,

01:10:31.670 --> 01:10:32.667
but paying attention to what other people

01:10:32.667 --> 01:10:34.100
are paying attention to.

01:10:34.100 --> 01:10:35.900
It seems to come up again and again.

01:10:37.720 --> 01:10:39.190
Slightly off center from that,

01:10:39.190 --> 01:10:40.370
but still paying attention to what

01:10:40.370 --> 01:10:42.220
other people are paying attention to.

01:10:43.210 --> 01:10:46.263
What's known about jealousy
in men versus women?

01:10:47.779 --> 01:10:50.430
And how frequent it is, how intense it is,

01:10:50.430 --> 01:10:52.490
and what people do with that jealousy.

01:10:52.490 --> 01:10:54.180
I mean, we hear,

01:10:54.180 --> 01:10:56.337
or I've heard at some point that

01:10:56.337 --> 01:10:57.450
a large fraction of homicides

01:10:57.450 --> 01:11:00.043
are the consequence of jealous lovers.

01:11:01.370 --> 01:11:03.640
That's the darkest angle of all this,

01:11:03.640 --> 01:11:08.640
but in evolutionary psychology
context, what is jealousy?

01:11:10.450 --> 01:11:13.210
Does it relate to paternity issues only?

01:11:13.210 --> 01:11:14.180
What can you tell us about jealousy?

01:11:14.180 --> 01:11:18.330
Yeah, that's great set of questions,

01:11:18.330 --> 01:11:20.940
and when I first started
studying jealousy,

01:11:20.940 --> 01:11:24.150
I reviewed all the prior
publications on jealousy.

01:11:24.150 --> 01:11:26.240
And at that time,

01:11:26.240 --> 01:11:31.240
jealousy was regarded
as a sign of immaturity,

01:11:31.630 --> 01:11:34.263
a sign of insecurity,

01:11:35.440 --> 01:11:38.360
a sign of a neurosis or pathology,

01:11:38.360 --> 01:11:40.773
or in some cases delusion.

01:11:41.660 --> 01:11:45.210
And what I argued is,

01:11:45.210 --> 01:11:49.210
and do argue, is that
jealousy is an evolved emotion

01:11:49.210 --> 01:11:52.780
that serves several
adaptive functions, okay?

01:11:52.780 --> 01:11:53.790
One of which you mentioned

01:11:53.790 --> 01:11:56.263
is a paternity certainty function.

01:11:57.150 --> 01:12:00.490
But to back up a second,

01:12:00.490 --> 01:12:01.990
basically, once you have the evolution

01:12:01.990 --> 01:12:04.470
of long-term mating, long-term pair bonds,

01:12:04.470 --> 01:12:07.260
you're talking about
from a male perspective,

01:12:07.260 --> 01:12:10.027
investing a tremendous amount
of resources in a woman

01:12:10.027 --> 01:12:13.830
and her children over years or decades,

01:12:13.830 --> 01:12:15.380
even with boomerang kids now,

01:12:15.380 --> 01:12:17.830
it may go more than two decades.

01:12:17.830 --> 01:12:19.230
- Boomerang kids?

01:12:19.230 --> 01:12:23.175
- Kids who leave home and then
come back and live at home.

01:12:23.175 --> 01:12:24.570
- That happens?

01:12:24.570 --> 01:12:25.530
- Oh yeah, that happens.

01:12:25.530 --> 01:12:26.620
- I don't have children.

01:12:26.620 --> 01:12:29.170
- Okay yeah, no that's a big thing.

01:12:29.170 --> 01:12:32.496
- But if I do I'll just
expect that they'll come back.

01:12:32.496 --> 01:12:34.120
- They'll come back because
they can't find a job,

01:12:34.120 --> 01:12:35.320
or they find it cheaper

01:12:35.320 --> 01:12:37.560
to live at the parent's
house, or whatever.

01:12:37.560 --> 01:12:38.393
- Oh, goodness.

01:12:38.393 --> 01:12:39.226
I can't think of anything worse.

01:12:39.226 --> 01:12:40.400
I mean, I love my parents.

01:12:41.340 --> 01:12:44.180
- I know, I can't imagine,

01:12:44.180 --> 01:12:47.080
but it happens and it's
happening more and more,

01:12:47.080 --> 01:12:49.680
given the current economic situation.

01:12:49.680 --> 01:12:52.790
But, so once you have long-term mating,

01:12:52.790 --> 01:12:56.440
you need a defense

01:12:56.440 --> 01:12:59.440
to prevent or preserve the investment

01:12:59.440 --> 01:13:02.500
that you've made and are
making in long-term mateship.

01:13:02.500 --> 01:13:06.650
And so jealousy serves this
mate guarding function,

01:13:06.650 --> 01:13:08.960
if you will, or mate retention function.

01:13:08.960 --> 01:13:12.010
So in other words, one
way of phrasing this,

01:13:12.010 --> 01:13:14.950
is that we know that they are affairs,

01:13:14.950 --> 01:13:17.350
we know that people break
up, they get divorced,

01:13:18.250 --> 01:13:20.740
but people have adaptations

01:13:20.740 --> 01:13:23.900
to want to hold on to their mates, okay?

01:13:23.900 --> 01:13:25.800
And that's what jealousy's in part about.

01:13:25.800 --> 01:13:29.220
And so jealousy gets activated
when there are threats

01:13:29.220 --> 01:13:31.540
to that romantic relationship.

01:13:31.540 --> 01:13:33.480
And there are other forms of jealousy,

01:13:33.480 --> 01:13:35.090
like sibling jealousy and so forth,

01:13:35.090 --> 01:13:38.480
but we're focusing on mating
jealousy in this context.

01:13:38.480 --> 01:13:42.860
So now what's interesting
is that the threats

01:13:42.860 --> 01:13:46.460
to an ongoing, valued
romantic relationship

01:13:46.460 --> 01:13:48.150
come from many sources.

01:13:48.150 --> 01:13:48.983
So they could be,

01:13:48.983 --> 01:13:52.273
you detect cues to your
partner's infidelity,

01:13:53.941 --> 01:13:58.941
or cues of a lack of an emotional distance

01:13:58.960 --> 01:14:01.100
between you and your partner.

01:14:01.100 --> 01:14:03.040
You say, I love you to your partner,

01:14:03.040 --> 01:14:05.040
and your partner says,

01:14:05.040 --> 01:14:06.720
I wonder how the hell the Knicks are doing

01:14:06.720 --> 01:14:08.460
this scoring season, or whatever.

01:14:08.460 --> 01:14:11.600
If you get an unreciprocated
I love you is a bad cue.

01:14:11.600 --> 01:14:13.870
- Or a half, or some people
are so tuned to this,

01:14:13.870 --> 01:14:16.570
if there's a half millisecond delay,

01:14:16.570 --> 01:14:18.590
they can detect delays in responses.

01:14:18.590 --> 01:14:19.423
- Yes, yeah.

01:14:19.423 --> 01:14:22.390
Delays in responses, but even things like,

01:14:22.390 --> 01:14:25.290
so that's one set of cues,

01:14:25.290 --> 01:14:28.450
but then there's another set
of interested mate poachers.

01:14:28.450 --> 01:14:32.330
So, you know, if you're mated
to someone who's desirable,

01:14:32.330 --> 01:14:35.350
which many people are, other
people still desire them,

01:14:35.350 --> 01:14:37.700
and so sometimes try to poach them,

01:14:37.700 --> 01:14:39.590
or lure them away from you

01:14:39.590 --> 01:14:42.110
for a short term sexual encounter,

01:14:42.110 --> 01:14:44.750
or for a longer term relationship.

01:14:44.750 --> 01:14:47.550
And so we have to be, so
jealousy motivates people

01:14:47.550 --> 01:14:50.010
to be attentive to potential mate poachers

01:14:50.010 --> 01:14:51.770
in their environment,

01:14:51.770 --> 01:14:56.720
but even more subtle things
like mate value discrepancies

01:14:56.720 --> 01:14:58.330
can trigger jealousy.

01:14:58.330 --> 01:15:00.250
So even if there are no mate poachers

01:15:00.250 --> 01:15:02.350
and no accused infidelity,

01:15:02.350 --> 01:15:06.650
if a mate value discrepancy
opens up in a relationship.

01:15:06.650 --> 01:15:08.450
So in the American system,

01:15:08.450 --> 01:15:11.690
like you're a six or an eight or a ten,

01:15:11.690 --> 01:15:13.800
and people generally pair off

01:15:13.800 --> 01:15:15.680
based on similarity and mate value.

01:15:15.680 --> 01:15:18.200
- So that tends to happen,
sixes end up with sixes,

01:15:18.200 --> 01:15:20.493
sevens end up with
sixes, plus or minus one.

01:15:21.700 --> 01:15:23.730
These are somewhat subjective scales.

01:15:23.730 --> 01:15:24.610
- Somewhat subjective,

01:15:24.610 --> 01:15:27.440
but there's still some
consensus about these things.

01:15:27.440 --> 01:15:30.040
So even colloquially people,

01:15:30.040 --> 01:15:32.233
colloquially people say things like,

01:15:33.160 --> 01:15:35.280
he's not good enough for you, you know,

01:15:35.280 --> 01:15:38.640
or I think you could do better to people

01:15:38.640 --> 01:15:41.500
who implicitly have a notion
of relative mate value

01:15:41.500 --> 01:15:43.500
and discrepancies therein,

01:15:43.500 --> 01:15:47.810
but discrepancies can open up
where none previously existed.

01:15:47.810 --> 01:15:50.040
So you get fired from a job.

01:15:50.040 --> 01:15:51.570
All of a sudden, you know,

01:15:51.570 --> 01:15:53.820
and most people are very understanding

01:15:53.820 --> 01:15:56.240
and forgiving about that,

01:15:56.240 --> 01:15:59.250
if it's not too long, but you
go six months, eight months,

01:15:59.250 --> 01:16:02.000
people start having problems,

01:16:02.000 --> 01:16:03.930
or if someone's career takes off.

01:16:03.930 --> 01:16:07.730
Let's say a woman becomes
a famous singer or actress,

01:16:07.730 --> 01:16:10.870
or a man does, career takes off.

01:16:10.870 --> 01:16:13.270
All of a sudden there's
a mate value discrepancy

01:16:13.270 --> 01:16:16.380
where you have access to a
larger pool of potential mates

01:16:16.380 --> 01:16:18.743
and higher mate value potential mates.

01:16:19.580 --> 01:16:22.240
So, people are attentive to
mate value discrepancies.

01:16:22.240 --> 01:16:24.690
And so jealousy can get activated,

01:16:24.690 --> 01:16:28.720
even if there are no immediate
threats to a relationship,

01:16:28.720 --> 01:16:32.050
but the mate value discrepancy is a threat

01:16:32.050 --> 01:16:34.860
that looms on the horizon
of the relationship,

01:16:34.860 --> 01:16:38.840
because we know statistically
the higher mate value person

01:16:38.840 --> 01:16:42.380
is more likely to have an
affair and is more likely

01:16:42.380 --> 01:16:46.140
to dump the other person and
trade up in the mating market.

01:16:46.140 --> 01:16:49.410
- And when people find new partners

01:16:49.410 --> 01:16:52.910
for long-term relationships,
do they tend to trade up?

01:16:52.910 --> 01:16:54.193
- On average yes,

01:16:55.388 --> 01:16:57.533
if the discrepancy is sufficiently large,

01:16:58.470 --> 01:17:01.053
so there are costs
associated with breaking up,

01:17:01.960 --> 01:17:05.790
divorcing for example, I
mean, it's emotionally,

01:17:05.790 --> 01:17:08.270
financially, it's a costly thing.

01:17:08.270 --> 01:17:11.180
And so if you have like a half a point

01:17:11.180 --> 01:17:12.680
mate value discrepancy,

01:17:12.680 --> 01:17:15.140
you're not going to see a lot
of breakups, but you know,

01:17:15.140 --> 01:17:17.320
if you have larger mate
value discrepancies,

01:17:17.320 --> 01:17:21.313
that's going to augur more for
trading up in the mating market.

01:17:22.440 --> 01:17:26.650
So, then you get into,

01:17:26.650 --> 01:17:27.860
so what jealousy is,

01:17:27.860 --> 01:17:31.720
it's an emotion that gets
activated by these circumstances.

01:17:31.720 --> 01:17:33.310
And then what people do about it

01:17:33.310 --> 01:17:36.010
depends on what their options are.

01:17:36.010 --> 01:17:38.260
And people do things that I,

01:17:38.260 --> 01:17:40.400
in my published scientific work,

01:17:40.400 --> 01:17:43.550
I say range from vigilance to violence.

01:17:43.550 --> 01:17:45.400
So this whole spectrum of things.

01:17:45.400 --> 01:17:48.040
In fact, I've identified
19 different tactics

01:17:48.040 --> 01:17:53.040
that people use to deal with
problems once they get jealous,

01:17:53.540 --> 01:17:55.640
and one is increased vigilance,

01:17:55.640 --> 01:17:56.473
and the other extreme violence.

01:17:56.473 --> 01:17:59.120
- Vigilance for the behavior of the mate.

01:17:59.120 --> 01:18:01.080
- Yeah, vigilance for
the behavior of the mate.

01:18:01.080 --> 01:18:05.210
And that can include stalking, following,

01:18:05.210 --> 01:18:08.093
hacking into iPhones or computers,

01:18:09.100 --> 01:18:13.700
monitoring the behavior of mate poachers,

01:18:13.700 --> 01:18:18.190
looking at eye contact between
other men and your partner.

01:18:18.190 --> 01:18:20.770
There's a whole suite
of things that you know,

01:18:20.770 --> 01:18:22.713
is involved in vigilance.

01:18:23.960 --> 01:18:25.630
And then at the other extreme,

01:18:25.630 --> 01:18:27.180
and we can talk about things in between,

01:18:27.180 --> 01:18:29.290
but the other extreme is violence.

01:18:29.290 --> 01:18:32.700
And so in my new book,
When Men Behave Badly,

01:18:32.700 --> 01:18:35.590
I have a whole chapter on
intimate partner violence.

01:18:35.590 --> 01:18:37.877
And this is what I argue,

01:18:37.877 --> 01:18:42.250
and this is really unfortunate,
and I'm not endorsing it.

01:18:42.250 --> 01:18:44.720
