01:58:06.540 --> 01:58:09.610
because it's sufficiently complicated.

01:58:09.610 --> 01:58:13.420
So I mentioned, you know,
we've mentioned maybe half,

01:58:13.420 --> 01:58:16.840
maybe a dozen different
components of mate value,

01:58:16.840 --> 01:58:19.810
physical attractiveness,
kindness, emotional stability,

01:58:19.810 --> 01:58:21.333
health status, et cetera.

01:58:23.110 --> 01:58:24.830
And these aren't the only ones.

01:58:24.830 --> 01:58:28.600
So I teach a course on
psychology of human mating.

01:58:28.600 --> 01:58:30.760
And I ask the people, it's a large course,

01:58:30.760 --> 01:58:32.320
a couple of hundred people,

01:58:32.320 --> 01:58:34.760
tell me, what do women want in a mate?

01:58:34.760 --> 01:58:36.620
And so I start it with the blackboard.

01:58:36.620 --> 01:58:38.000
This is back in the old days

01:58:38.000 --> 01:58:40.410
when there was a blackboard, a
piece of chalk, and they say,

01:58:40.410 --> 01:58:42.120
I want a mate who has
a good sense of humor.

01:58:42.120 --> 01:58:43.460
So I write sense of humor.

01:58:43.460 --> 01:58:45.300
Intelligent, kind.

01:58:45.300 --> 01:58:49.020
And so I go through this, and
I go through five blackboards,

01:58:49.020 --> 01:58:51.780
and then I run out of
space, over what women want.

01:58:51.780 --> 01:58:52.707
Now I do the same for men,

01:58:52.707 --> 01:58:54.320
and men kind of run out of space

01:58:54.320 --> 01:58:56.180
after about a blackboard and a half.

01:58:56.180 --> 01:59:00.300
But what that tells me
is that these qualities

01:59:00.300 --> 01:59:02.960
are large in number and
complicated in nature.

01:59:02.960 --> 01:59:06.810
So you say you want a guy
who's nice and generous?

01:59:06.810 --> 01:59:07.643
And they say, yeah.

01:59:07.643 --> 01:59:09.570
So like a guy who at
the end of every month

01:59:09.570 --> 01:59:10.610
takes his whole paycheck

01:59:10.610 --> 01:59:14.080
and gives it to the
wino, a homeless person.

01:59:14.080 --> 01:59:17.450
Well no, not that generous,
generous toward me,

01:59:17.450 --> 01:59:19.580
but not toward everyone else.

01:59:19.580 --> 01:59:21.210
Nice in general,

01:59:21.210 --> 01:59:24.930
but not so nice that
they're getting exploited.

01:59:24.930 --> 01:59:27.710
So, or even, now there's something,

01:59:27.710 --> 01:59:29.290
you can't be too healthy.

01:59:29.290 --> 01:59:31.470
So if you put it, that's uni-dimensional,

01:59:31.470 --> 01:59:32.580
but you want a guy,

01:59:32.580 --> 01:59:36.800
women want a guy who's
confident, but not too confident,

01:59:36.800 --> 01:59:39.240
because too confident will
mean he's either arrogant,

01:59:39.240 --> 01:59:43.223
narcissistic, or not
sufficiently manipulable.

01:59:45.450 --> 01:59:47.750
So anyway, my point is that

01:59:47.750 --> 01:59:48.840
because there are so many

01:59:48.840 --> 01:59:50.940
different components of mate value,

01:59:50.940 --> 01:59:54.410
and that they vary in amount.

01:59:54.410 --> 01:59:57.210
So it's not just listing the
qualities and summing them up.

01:59:57.210 --> 01:59:58.630
They vary in amount.

01:59:58.630 --> 02:00:02.430
It's a very complicated
endeavor to assess accurately,

02:00:02.430 --> 02:00:06.000
but I think people have
a good intuitive sense

02:00:06.000 --> 02:00:08.200
of people's relative mate value,

02:00:08.200 --> 02:00:10.280
especially if you're in a group

02:00:10.280 --> 02:00:13.040
and you've been able to interact
with them for a long time.

02:00:13.040 --> 02:00:17.530
And one indication is, again,
that attention structure.

02:00:17.530 --> 02:00:18.970
How many other people

02:00:18.970 --> 02:00:20.920
will really want to mate with this person?

02:00:20.920 --> 02:00:23.550
That's a good cue that
they're high in mate value.

02:00:23.550 --> 02:00:25.170
Nobody wants to mate with you,

02:00:25.170 --> 02:00:27.543
then cue that your low in mate value.

02:00:28.470 --> 02:00:30.900
- Reminds of the time when
one is trying to decide

02:00:30.900 --> 02:00:32.313
who to ask to the prom.

02:00:33.750 --> 02:00:35.650
There's a complicated assessment

02:00:35.650 --> 02:00:38.240
based on who one would like to go with,

02:00:38.240 --> 02:00:40.140
whether or not you're already partnered,

02:00:40.140 --> 02:00:41.580
who would say yes, who would say no,

02:00:41.580 --> 02:00:43.780
because there's a risk in rejection too,

02:00:43.780 --> 02:00:47.430
because that if I'm guessing correctly,

02:00:47.430 --> 02:00:50.980
could lower one's own
perceived mate value.

02:00:50.980 --> 02:00:52.310
- Getting rejected.
- Right.

02:00:52.310 --> 02:00:55.090
Frequency of rejections probably
doesn't lend itself well

02:00:55.090 --> 02:00:59.600
to increasing one's own
view of their mate value.

02:00:59.600 --> 02:01:01.870
- Right, which is why many guys have

02:01:01.870 --> 02:01:04.750
what I call mating anxiety.

02:01:04.750 --> 02:01:08.180
That is, they don't approach women

02:01:08.180 --> 02:01:10.460
because they risk getting shot down.

02:01:10.460 --> 02:01:13.033
- They're trying to maintain that number,

02:01:14.320 --> 02:01:16.440
by reducing the amount of data.

02:01:16.440 --> 02:01:17.850
- [David] Right.

02:01:17.850 --> 02:01:18.950
- Very interesting.

02:01:18.950 --> 02:01:23.005
- But it backfires in
the modern environment.

02:01:23.005 --> 02:01:25.660
So, there's a famous
psychologist, Albert Ellis,

02:01:25.660 --> 02:01:29.110
who had mating anxiety and
he assigned himself the task

02:01:29.110 --> 02:01:31.140
of asking, like,

02:01:31.140 --> 02:01:32.430
I can't remember what the number was,

02:01:32.430 --> 02:01:34.900
but let's say 50 women out on dates.

02:01:34.900 --> 02:01:37.210
He lived in New York City,
so there was a lot of women.

02:01:37.210 --> 02:01:39.507
- He could just stand still
and they would stream past him.

02:01:39.507 --> 02:01:44.507
- And he asked 50 women on a
date, you know, every week.

02:01:45.060 --> 02:01:47.840
And he said, after two weeks
his mating anxiety disappeared,

02:01:47.840 --> 02:01:50.887
because most of them said, buzz off creep,

02:01:50.887 --> 02:01:52.450
[indistinct]

02:01:52.450 --> 02:01:55.250
Actually getting rejected didn't
cause my world to collapse.

02:01:55.250 --> 02:01:56.387
And it actually was okay.

02:01:56.387 --> 02:02:00.180
And so he kind of inured
himself to this rejection.

02:02:00.180 --> 02:02:02.950
And so it ended up,

02:02:02.950 --> 02:02:05.090
he ended up doing quite
well on his mating life.

02:02:05.090 --> 02:02:08.130
